The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: Preferences extracted: I favor well‑produced, studio‑polished hits collections in the Phil Collins vein — clear, forward lead vocals, punchy/concise arrangements, memorable hooks and sing‑along choruses, and varied tempos/moods that reward repeat listens. I value single‑artist hit anthologies when they’re curated and sonically rich, with strong mastering and a sense of curation. I dislike abrasive, guitar‑driven proto‑punk grit and any poorly mastered, flattened/over‑compressed releases or overly homogeneous, radio‑polished greatest‑hits discs.
Evaluation and choice reasoning:
- Roxette (Don't Bore Us Get to the Chorus) aligns directly with the primary, stated taste for studio‑polished pop hit collections. Roxette’s catalogue is built around clear, forward lead vocals, strong melodic hooks and big sing‑along choruses (their major hits are archetypal pop singles), and a mix of uptempo tracks and ballads that provide the tempo/mood variety I prize. As a greatest‑hits anthology it is precisely the kind of single‑artist, hits‑focused collection I said I gravitate toward: immediate, hook‑driven songs that reward repeat listening and sit well in a CD-centric, high‑fidelity context. Importantly, Roxette’s production style is pop‑polish rather than the abrasive, saturated, distortion-heavy guitar sound I actively dislike, so it avoids the proto‑punk qualities I want to reject.
- Boston’s greatest hits, while described with very strong mastering, preserved dynamics, and lush production — attributes I also value — is an AOR/arena‑rock collection built around multi‑tracked guitars and very layered arrangements. That makes it sonically rich and ideal for full‑disc, high‑fidelity listening (a clear plus), but it leans more toward guitar‑forward, album‑crafted production rather than the concise, vocal‑forward pop singles I specifically said I gravitate to. In other words, Boston matches my standards for mastering and sonics but is a different aesthetic: denser, guitar‑centric arrangements and extended album‑style production that can be less immediate and sing‑along friendly than the tight pop singles I prefer.
Decision summary:
Because my primary preference is for well‑produced, vocal‑forward pop hit anthologies with punchy arrangements, memorable hooks and varied tempos, Roxette’s greatest‑hits collection better matches those specific criteria. Boston is attractively mastered and sonically excellent, but its AOR, guitar‑layered, album‑crafted approach is a step away from the concise, Phil Collins–style pop hits I most enjoy, so I reject it in favor of the Roxette compilation.

