- The anthology’s fuller remastering that opens orchestral layers and dynamic solos speaks directly to my demand for strong mastering with clear dynamics; orchestral‑pop benefits from careful remastering, which preserves separation, punch and clarity—precisely what I look for on CD. The rich liner notes and tactile multi‑disc sequencing also fulfill my desire for informative packaging and sense of curation.
- Madonna’s Like A Prayer is an excellent, well‑produced studio album and meets many of my production preferences (vocal‑forward, hook‑rich, polished mastering). However, compared to the anthology it is more stylistically homogeneous and offers less of the variety/discovery and archival value I prize in a CD purchase. Because I emphasized curated anthologies and expanded collector‑grade releases (with alternate mixes, deep cuts and detailed notes) over a single cohesive studio album—even a great one—the ELO anthology better matches my overall criteria.
- Finally, neither candidate triggers my dislikes (no proto‑punk grit or obvious poor mastering), but the anthology’s broader scope, thoughtful remastering and documented curation make it the superior fit for my collector‑oriented, discovery‑focused CD preferences.

